Tina, I think you just have to be up-front about it.
All you can say is &quot;This is what I'll pay you for it,
and I'll have to price it higher, of course, to allow
some profit when I sell it. Normally, I pay about
50% of what I think it will sell for, BUT I have to
mark it higher than that because everyone wants
a discount at an antique shop, which they'd never
ask for at Nordstrom.&quot;

It's amazing that most people don't realize that *all*
retailers have to mark up their items, to stay in
business and allow a profit.

People act shocked if they hear that Nordstrom's
marks everything up 100% - like they're stealing
or something.

Everyone here is probably sick of my story, but
just in case:
An antique shop owner in Utah bought some things
from a woman. Fairly nice things, including a piece
of glass that she gave the women $100 for. A
couple of weeks later, the woman returned to the
shop and noticed that the glass piece was marked
$220. The woman left, then returned (accompanied
by the police). She told the police that the antique
store had robbed her, because she was trying to
sell the item for more than she'd been paid. The
policeman started laughing, and had to give his
first speech on retailing.

Kris

