I have to say that when I go to a shop or show where items have no prices I
assume they are out of my price range, so I look around and leave. This may
or not be true, but I find it discouraging that a shop or booth at a show
doesn't give me, as a shopper, a baseline on which to base the general level
of merchandise they carry.

As an example, I was at a show and saw a lovely pair of brass candlesticks.
They were not marked with a price. I talked to the dealer (who was very nice)
and found out they were American, mid 1700s, and way beyond my means. As a
result, the dealer spent her time unproductively because I could never afford
them, and I would have know that if they were marked.

I understand that making personal contact with a shopper can make a
difference in a sale, but sometimes it is a waste of time for the dealer and
the shopper.

With regard to the original poster's problem, I have worked in grocery
stores, gourmet food stores and gift shops. If the general public knew what
their cherished Hallmark limited edition Christmas ornaments cost wholesale
they would spit. This is the reality of the retail business. You buy low and
sell high or you close your doors.

Marie

