"/> I agree with the points you make. However time is something you usually
have a lot of when your working in an antique shop. I don't know how it is
in the US, but here, even a shop in Oslo with top location will normally
have somewhere between 10 and 20 visits a day.

Furthermore I think too much focus these days are on the price of a piece.
That is what people watch the Antique Roadshow and similar programs - and
the result is a lot of really irritating bargain hunters. These days
everyone expect to find a Monet in the addict and a Delft Garniture in a
garagesale. The result is that a very high percentage of those who have an
interest in antiques end up spending all their money on junk.

It is particularly annoying on antique fairs. You can spot the bargain
hunters a mile away. The head straight for the messiest stalls where they
look at everything, because they don't care what they buy as long as it is
dead cheap. And should they by chance walk past a good display, they will
check one piece, see that it is clean and correctly marked, and then just
shake their empty heads in disbelief (some drop the head-shaking and in
stead gives you an angry look or yells &quot;idiot&quot; at you).

I have found that dropping the price tags will normally discourage most of
these. And if not, when they ask you can just look at their clothes in a
surprised manner, raise one eyebrow and smile forgivingly.

Then again, of course, I go bargain hunting too. That is how I make a
living. I guess the only difference is that I don't see buying antiques as
a substitute for playing bingo, but rather try to make a profit from the
more stable percentages.

Cheers,
CZ.

